[codex] ## I. Strict-consistency rules (apply uniformly across studies)
[codex] 
[codex] ### I.1 Lead-in sentence(s)
[codex] - 1 to 2 sentences right after the `Study X` heading.
[codex] - Establishes the paradigm (NPR producers, biographies on campus, Facebook biopic ad, library reading list, panel selection) and what manipulation is being tested.
[codex] - Pattern in Study 1: "In Study X, participants imagined [paradigm]. We tested whether [feedback condition]ΓÇª"
[codex] - Pattern in Study 3B: "In this study, we sought to replicate our key findings from Study 3A about [variation]ΓÇª"
[codex] - **DO NOT** restate full theoretical motivation (lives in the Introduction).
[codex] - **DO** name the focal feedback dimension (gender, race) explicitly.
[codex] 
[codex] ### I.2 Methods header structure
[codex] - `Methods` is the section header (HEADING_2).
[codex] - `Participants.` and `Procedure.` are bold paragraph leads (NOT separate headings).
[codex] - For Studies with measure-specific paragraphs (4A, 4B, 5), the bold leads also include `Internal motivationΓÇª`, `External motivationΓÇª`, `Political ideology.`, `Political party affiliation.`, etc.
[codex] 
[codex] ### I.3 Participants line ΓÇö canonical structure
[codex] Single sentence, semicolon-delimited fields, in this order:
[codex] 
[codex] ```
[codex] Participants. As pre-registered (https://OSF/AsPredicted/...), we recruited N participants on/through PLATFORM to complete a [Y]-minute survey for $[Z] (gender breakdown; Mage = X.XX; race breakdown).
[codex] ```
[codex] 
[codex] Evidence (Study 1): `As pre-registered (https://osf.io/vazsm/), we recruited 1,000 participants through Prolific to complete a 3-minute survey for $0.75 (55.4% women; 43.7% men; 0.9% non-binary; Mage = 43.80; 72.3% White, 13.2% Black, 6.5% Hispanic, 7.2% Asian).`
[codex] 
[codex] Evidence (Study 3B): `As pre-registered (https://osf.io/uyn8g/), we recruited 1,000 participants on Cloudresearch to complete a 3-minute survey for $0.75 (51.0% men; 48.3% women; Mage = 43.60; 77.9% White, 9.7% Black, 5.5% Hispanic, 6.4% Asian).`
[codex] 
[codex] Sub-rules:
[codex] - **Gender order is whichever group is larger in the actual sample**, not a fixed convention. Study 1 women first (55.4% > 43.7%); Study 3B men first (51.0% > 48.3%). Match each study's source.
[codex] - **Include `non-binary` (or whatever the sample produced) when present.** Study 1 has 0.9% non-binary; Studies 2 and 3B do not.
[codex] - **Use semicolons between gender-breakdown fields, between gender and Mage, and between Mage and race breakdown.** Use commas only inside the race breakdown.
[codex] - **Mage formatting:** `Mage = XX.XX` (two decimals). The M is italicized and `age` is subscripted in the Word render; in markdown source we just write `Mage`.
[codex] - Eligibility criteria (90% approval, 1,000+ prior completions, U.S.-based) are NOT in the participants line ΓÇö they live in footnote B1 anchored at Study 1 (per Katy red line #1).
[codex] - Study 2 is the one outlier on this rule: it uses TWO sentences (`This study was pre-registered on AsPredicted (...). We recruited 302 participants...`) because of the field-setting context (recruiting at a campus location, dates of data collection, IRB consent waiver in the same paragraph). Studies 1, 3A, 3B, 4A, 4B, 5 use the single-sentence canonical form.
[codex] 
